800-05-004	API Authentication Criteria	
The following authentication criteria must be met in API/Middleware implementations:

All API calls must be properly authenticated in accordance with this TUG and the IS Standards (no implicit trust). 
A Bank-approved Identity Provider (IdP) must be used for all API authentication services. 
Only the following authentication methods are permissible, in order of preference: 
OAuth 2.0 Access Tokens 
Mutual TLS (mTLS) using certificate from Bank-approved CA 
Basic Authentication over encrypted channel (as a last resort only and requiring ECSO approval) 
Personal Access Tokens (e.g., for Github) must only be employed on an exceptional basis, and with explicit ECSO approval to authenticate/authorize user-to-service API calls (i.e., OAuth demonstrated to be non-viable integration method). 
Authentication materials/credentials must be properly secured. OAuth 2.0 and Basic Authentication credentials must be stored in a Bank-approved vault (eg, Cyberark/PAM, Apigee) and must not be embedded in code or configuration files.
The use of token passthrough is not permitted. Gateways must generate a properly scoped token for accessing services on the far side of the call. The actor's presented token should be mapped to an appropriate scope to ensure the original context is maintained.
