800-05-006	API OAuth Configuration Criteria	
OAuth2.0 is the preferred method for authenticating and authorizing API calls. Integrations must adhere to the following guidelines: 

Access Tokens must only be issued following successful authentication of the user or service, by the approved Identity Provider, in the context of an OAuth2.0 Grant 
Supported Grants include: OpenID Connect Authorization Code with PKCE (user flows); OAuth2.0 Authorization Code with PKCE (user flows); Authorization Code (user flows); and Client Credentials (non-human flows). Use of implicit flow is prohibited. 
Access Tokens must contain authorization information (i.e., scopes and/or user claims) to support coarse-grained authorization decisions by the API implementation. 
Access Tokens must be cryptographically signed to ensure their integrity.
Access Token Time to Live (TTL) must be set, and the duration must be as short as possible (industry guidelines are 5-15 minutes) and not to exceed 60 minutes. A refresh token may be used to maintain user sessions. However, the TTL should be strictly limited and must not exceed 30 days, after which re-authentication is required.
Access Tokens must be restricted to certain resources (audience restriction), preferably to a single resource server. 
Access Tokens should be sender-constrained (eg, mTLS, DPoP). Sender-constrained Access Tokens scope the applicability of access tokens to a dedicated sender. In this scenario, the resource server verifies that the token originates from a known and authorized source and is valid, before giving the required access to the resources. 
Sensitive data must not be included in Access Tokens, unless the data is encrypted or otherwise obfuscated (eg, opaque tokens). 
Tokens – specifically Access and Refresh – returned to an end-user’s browser must not be stored via Browser Persistent Storage APIs (e.g., LocalStorage, SessionStorage, IndexedDB).

